@menghaoranss
i am thinking of keeping the impl like this,
public static OrchestrationInstance init(final String instanceTag) {
        if (null == instance) {
            synchronized (OrchestrationInstance.class) {
                if (null == instance) {
                    instance = new OrchestrationInstance(instanceTag);
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }

    public static String getInstanceId() {
        if (null == instance) {
            throw new IllegalStateException("OrchestrationInstance not initialized!");
        }
        return instance.instanceId;
    }

but because of this code InstanceStateChangedListenerTest.setUp() throws the IllegalStateException.
Will need to refactor the test-case as well.
Should this be ok? I believe in reality there will be no case when getInstanceId() will be called before setting up of RegistryCenter and its just how TC are written.

I can understand the meaning of your code above, but I think it is too complicated, below is my suggestion:
@Getter
public final class OrchestrationInstance {

    private static final String DELIMITER = "@";

    private static final OrchestrationInstance INSTANCE = new OrchestrationInstance();

    private String instanceId;

    private OrchestrationInstance() {

    }

    public void init(final String instanceTag) {
        instanceId = IpUtils.getIp() + DELIMITER + instanceTag + DELIMITER + UUID.randomUUID().toString();
    }

    /**
     * Get instance.
     * 
     * @return instance
     */
    public static OrchestrationInstance getInstance() {
        return INSTANCE;
    }
}

@menghaoranss If we go ahead with this approach, we will risk someone calling getInstance() without ensuring init() was called and then returning an empty string as instanceId.
Moreover, this makes instanceId mutable i.e. anyone can do OrchestrationInstance.getInstance().init("a") and then OrchestrationInstance.getInstance().init("b")

Yes, we must guarantee that OrchestrationInstance only initialize once in the code，this is what we need to do.

